Window analysis game-by-game and player level

Austin Stephen

7/19/2021

Take Aways:

  • This is not capturing the refractory period due to fatigue (shows opposite actually).
  • This looks good for our rolling avg as a proxy for team strength as current performance is closely tied to performance over the last 5 games.
  • Need to do new windows of speed because it is time adjusted and this might help avoid players getting used more.

About the data:

Each observation is a single player in a single game. All players who were in the game for less than 15 seconds were removed. In total, It has 24k observations from the 2014-15 regular season.

  1. dist_miles = \(\beta_{0}\) + \(\beta_{1}\) (Sum_of_dist_5_days_prior)
    p-value \(\beta_{1}\) : <2e-16 (t statistic 115.2)

  2. diff_from_season_avg_distance = \(\beta_{0}\) + \(\beta_{1}\) (Sum_of_dist_5_days_prior)
    p-value \(\beta_{1}\) : <2e-16 (t statistic 31.93)

  3. diff_from_season_avg_distance = \(\beta_{0}\) + \(\beta_{1}\) (diff_from_season_avg_window_last_5_games)
    p-value \(\beta_{1}\) : <2e-16 (t statistic 41.910)

Testing window sizes of 3, 5, 7, 10 days

  • No difference

Only players who played more than 10 minutes

  • no difference in relationship

Relationship with preformance

  • Since we showed distance to be positively correlated with fg and fg3 percentage this small positive correlation makes sense.

  1. diff_from_season_avg_fg_pct = \(\beta_{0}\) + \(\beta_{1}\) (diff_sn_avg_wind_7_dist)
    p-value \(\beta_{1}\) : 1.55e-08 (t statistic 5.658)

  2. diff_from_season_avg_fg3_pct = \(\beta_{0}\) + \(\beta_{1}\) (diff_sn_avg_wind_7_dist)
    p-value \(\beta_{1}\) : 5.42e-07 (t statistic 5.012)
